# ops.publish-change-summary - rendered Markdown change summary.
#
# Referenced by rule `ops.change-summary`. The executor substitutes the
# ${...} placeholders with values from the ActionType arguments and the
# audit-log projection; a fork that ships a Confluence page publisher
# substitutes this template file with an equivalent storage-format XML
# body without touching the ActionType, the rule, or the Rego policy.
# ---
# ChangeSummary: `${scope_ref}` (last ${window_hours}h)

**Generated at**: `${generated_at}`
**Window**: `${window_start}` -> `${window_end}` (UTC)
**Resources touched**: ${resource_count}
**Change events**: ${change_count}

## What changed

The table below aggregates every resource-mutation event emitted by
the inventory adapter within the window, grouped by resource id.
Each entry cites the ActionType, the mode (shadow / enforce), and the
audit-log record id so a reviewer can drill into the underlying
decision.

| Resource | ActionType | Mode | Correlation |
|----------|------------|------|-------------|
${change_rows}

## How to read this

- Rows are sorted by ``observed_at``, oldest first. A resource that
  changed multiple times appears once per event.
- ``Mode`` is the mode at the time of the change, not the current
  ActionType default. A row marked ``enforce`` means the mutation was
  auto-applied; ``shadow`` means the executor judged and logged only.
- ``Correlation`` is the audit-log record id; look it up via the
  read-API ``/audit/{id}`` route for the full evidence chain (rule id,
  policy verdict, blast-radius trace).

## Follow-ups

- Any row with a stop-condition or rollback flag is out of scope for
  the summary body and MUST be triaged out-of-band via the audit log.
- This document is a projection of state at generation time; it does
  NOT itself trigger any action. Approve / reject the underlying
  changes through their own audit records, not by editing this file.
